From 70e8b84158fd1f3655c7945162e2c539e660efa7 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Thu, 16 Jul 2026 08:22:29 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 5/8] futex/vdso: Implement
 __vdso_futex_robust_list{64,32}_cmpxchg_rseq()

Cookie based robust futexes (ROBUST_LIST_COOKIE) require user space to
assign owner identifiers which are unique among all tasks sharing a
lock. For POSIX style process shared mutexes a practical way to
guarantee uniqueness without global coordination is a per lock
reservation counter: each lock attempt reserves a fresh counter value as
its cookie. As the counter is finite, reuse after a counter wrap must be
prevented. That requires that a lock attempt whose reservation was
outpaced by a counter epoch change can never store its stale cookie into
the lock word afterwards.

Provide VDSO functions which perform the user space lock acquisition of
a cookie based robust futex:

	*pending_ptr = NULL;
	if (!rseq->rseq_cs)
		return 0;
	*pending_ptr = pending;
	if (!atomic_try_cmpxchg(lock, &expect, set)) {
		*pending_ptr = NULL;
		return 0;
	}
	return 1;

with guarantees which pure user space code cannot provide:

 1) The region between the rseq_cs check and the cmpxchg is atomic
    versus RSEQ events. The caller stores a critical section descriptor,
    whose IP range does not contain any executed code, into
    TLS::rseq::rseq_cs before reserving the cookie. Any RSEQ event
    (preemption, signal delivery, RSEQ IPI) clears rseq_cs, so the check
    in the VDSO fails for a reservation which was interrupted before the
    function was reached. For an event hitting inside the VDSO critical
    section itself the kernel aborts the operation: it disarms the
    robust list pending op and moves the task to the abort landing pad,
    which makes the function return failure.

    Together with a quiescing mechanism which fences off all tasks
    sharing the lock (e.g. membarrier(), a subsequent change), this
    guarantees that no stale reservation survives a counter epoch
    change.

 2) Disarming the pending op after a failed cmpxchg is atomic versus
    signal delivery, mirroring the __vdso_futex_robust_try_unlock()
    protection. Otherwise a signal handler which does not return could
    leave a stale pending op armed for an unbounded time, whose cookie
    could eventually falsely match a later owner of the lock word at
    exit time.

 3) A task which dies without ever returning to user space (unhandled
    fatal signal: get_signal() invokes do_exit() directly, so neither
    the RSEQ event processing nor the signal delivery fixups run) does
    not leave an invalid pending op behind for the robust list exit walk
    to misinterpret. Two windows are fixed up at exit time, before the
    robust list is walked, by applying the signal delivery fixups
    against the task's user register frame:

      - Death inside the cmpxchg function before the cmpxchg committed:
        the cookie reservation was never validated and can be stale.

      - Death inside the try_unlock function after the unlock committed
        but before the pending op was disarmed: the lock was released
        and can have been legitimately re-acquired before the exit walk
        runs.

    In both cases a stale pending cookie can numerically match the
    (wrapped) cookie of the current live owner of the lock, so
    processing the pending op would misattribute the lock to the dead
    task and corrupt it. TID based and unique cookie setups are immune,
    as an identifier cannot be reused before the exit cleanup of its
    previous holder has run, but for counter based cookies these fixups
    are required for correctness. Both windows were found by model
    checking the counter protocol with TLC: the first during model
    construction, the second as a genuine model checker counterexample.

On success the reserved cookie is in the lock word and the pending op
stays armed - attributed through the task private list_op_pending_cookie
- until the caller has written the entry cookie and queued the entry in
the robust list, exactly like the list_op_pending protocol of the
original robust list. The shared entry cookie is only ever written after
success: a contender must never overwrite a live owner's entry cookie.

The distinction whether a fixup is required is based on the Zero
Flag. The rseq_cs check leaves ZF = 0 when it proceeds, MOV does not
modify flags and a successful cmpxchg sets ZF = 1. So ZF = 0 within the
critical section means the operation has not committed and must be
aborted. ZF = 1 means the operation either committed or is on its way to
the failure exit with the pending op already disarmed. In both cases no
fixup is required.

The abort fixup hooks into the RSEQ critical section handling: whenever
an RSEQ event results in clearing TLS::rseq::rseq_cs because the
instruction pointer is outside of the user space descriptor range, the
kernel checks whether the IP is inside the VDSO cmpxchg critical section
and applies the fixup. This covers preemption and interrupt induced
events via the exit to user path, RSEQ IPIs from membarrier() and signal
delivery via rseq_signal_deliver(). The clearing of the pending op via
put_user() is best effort for the RSEQ event cases: if it fails due to a
disabled pagefault handler, the abort landing pad in the VDSO disarms
the pending op again in user space. The signal delivery fixup cannot
rely on the landing pad: a signal handler which never returns through it
(siglongjmp, thread exit) would leave the stale pending op armed, and
the pending slot can be in a different page than the signal frame, so a
failing disarm does not imply that the frame setup fails as well. If the
signal time disarm fails, the robust list registration is dropped
instead (fail closed).

The pending op pointer is in DX in all build modes, so the kernel side
retrieval is uniform. As with the try_unlock functions two entry points
are provided to support multi-size robust list pointers used by gaming
emulators:

	__vdso_futex_robust_list64_cmpxchg_rseq()
	__vdso_futex_robust_list32_cmpxchg_rseq()

The 32-bit VDSO provides only the list32 variant.

This series was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
